05829nam a22008535i 9781442673700DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162004onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013955270  a97814426737007 a10.3138/97814426737002doi  a(DE-B1597)464386  a(OCoLC)944178294  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPN1993.5.I88bD37 2004eb 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/65122200aDante, Cinema, and Television /ced. by Amilcare Iannucci. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (270 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Italian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tDante and Hollywood -- tEarly Cinema, Dante's Inferno of 1911, and the Origins of Italian Film Culture -- tThe Helios-Psiche Dante Trilogy -- tBack to the Future: Dante and the Languages of Post-war Italian Film -- tBeginning to Think about Salò -- tThe Off-Screen Landscape: Dante's Ravenna and Antonioni's Red Desert -- tSpencer Williams and Dante: An African-American Filmmaker at the Gates of Hell -- tTelevision, Translation, and Vulgarization: Reflections on Phillips' and Greenaway's A TV Dante -- tDopo Tanto Veder: Pasolini's Dante after the Disappearance of the Fireflies -- t'Non Senti Come Tutto Questo Ti Assomiglia?' Fellini's Infernal Circles -- tDante and Canadian Cinema -- tDante and Cinema: Film across a Chasm -- tDante by Heart and Dante Declaimed: The 'Realization' of the Comedy on Italian Radio and Television -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex of Films -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Divine Comedy of Dante Alighieri (1265?1321) is one of the seminal works of western literature. Its impact on modern culture has been enormous, nourishing a plethora of twentieth century authors from Joyce and Borges to Kenzaburo Oe. Although Dante's influence in the literary sphere is well documented, very little has been written on his equally determining role in the evolution of the visual media unique to our times, namely, cinema and television. Dante, Cinema, and Television corrects this oversight.The essays, from a broad range of disciplines, cover the influence of the Divine Comedy from cinema's silent era on through to the era of sound and the advent of television, as well as its impact on specific directors, actors, and episodes, on national/regional cinema and television, and on genres. They also consider the different modes of appropriation by cinema and television. Dante, Cinema, and Television demonstrates the many subtle ways in which Dante's Divine Comedy has been given 'new life' by cinema and television, and underscores the tremendous extent of Dante's staying power in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMotion pictureszItaly. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aCaputo, Ring, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColonnese Benni, Vittoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFink, Guido, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIannucci, Amilcare A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIannucci, Amilcare, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKirkham, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLesperance, Gabrielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLooney, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRumble, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.